\pard\f0\fs28  An extremely variable species within which many infraspecific taxa have been recognized both in Europe and North Africa. The Italian populations have also frequently been segregated as four separate species, for which treatment there is some supporting karyological evidence (E. Maugini,{\i  Caryologia}{\b  5}: 167-177 (1953); {\b 8}: 370-378 (1956)):{\b  S. cupanii} Guss.,{\i  Fl. Sic. Prodr.}{\b  1}: 416 (1827), a more slender variant from Sicilia with 7 to 15(-20)-flowered corymbs, pedicels only 30-60 mm, much shorter than the bracts, perianth-segments up to 10 mm, and 2n = 14;{\b  S. sicula} Tineo ex Guss., {\i Fl. Sic. Syn.}{\b  2}: 813 (1845), from Calabria, Sicilia and Malta, with pedicels 40-60 mm, equalling the bracts, sparsely ciliate leaves, and perianth-segments whitish or violet;{\b  S. hughii} Tineo ex Guss.,{\i  Fl. Sic. Prodr., Suppl.} 162 (1832), endemic to Marettimo (Isole Egadi), with glabrous leaves 40-60 mm wide, deep violet perianth-segments and 2n = 16; and{\b  S. elongata} Parl.,{\i  Nuovi Gen. Sp. Monocot.} 24 (1854), a robust plant from Sicilia, Sardegna and perhaps Corse with densely ciliate leaves, ciliate bracts, pedicels 50-100 mm and perianth-segments 10-14 mm.
